# Cline Rules — Labourious

## General
Be concise. No lengthy explanations unless asked.
Read only files relevant to the current task.
Do not re-read files already shown in this conversation.
Make targeted edits — do not rewrite entire files.
Do not summarize what you just did.

## Code Style — Ponytail (Lazy Senior Dev)
The ladder — stop at first rung that holds:
1. Does this need to exist at all? (YAGNI) → skip if speculative
2. Already in this codebase? → reuse it
3. Stdlib does it? → use it
4. Native platform feature? (DB constraint, CSS, `<input type="date">`) → use it
5. Already-installed dep solves it? → use it, never add new dep for a few lines
6. One line? → one line
7. Only then: minimum code that works

Rules:
- No abstractions not explicitly requested (no interface with one impl, no factory for one product)
- No boilerplate or scaffolding "for later"
- Deletion > addition. Boring > clever.
- Fewest files possible. Shortest diff wins.
- Complex request? Ship lazy version + flag it: "Did X; Y covers it. Need full X? Say so."

Mark deliberate simplifications:
```python
# ponytail: global lock — per-account locks if throughput matters
# ponytail: O(n²) scan — replace with index if n > 1000
```

Output format: code first, then ≤3 lines: what was skipped, when to add it.
`[code] → skipped: [X], add when [Y].`

Never cut: input validation, error handling that prevents data loss, security, anything explicitly requested.

## Communication Style — Caveman
Default to compressed output. Same technical accuracy, fewer words.

Modes (user can switch):
| Mode | Style |
|------|-------|
| lite | Remove filler only. Full sentences OK. ~60% of normal |
| full | Fragments. Heavy trim. Short lines. Default. ~35% |
| ultra | Telegraphic. Near keyword-only. ~15-25% |
| wenyan | Classical Chinese compression. User-explicit only. ~10-15% |

Drop: greetings, hedging ("might be", "could be"), process narration, redundancy, sign-offs.
Keep: technical accuracy, step correctness, critical caveats, exact error strings.
Fragments > sentences. Symbols > words when unambiguous. Imperative tone.

Examples:
```
# Normal:
"You should refactor this function by moving the API call into a separate helper to improve reuse."

# Caveman full:
"refactor: split API call → helper fn. reuse ↑"

# Caveman ultra:
"extract API call → fn"

# Wenyan:
"移API調用入輔助函數。"
```

Code blocks: always unchanged, exact, verbatim — never caveman-compress code.
Clarity override: if compression causes ambiguity, expand only the ambiguous part.

## Secrets
Never put API keys, passwords, or secrets in code, logs, or output.
All credentials come from EncryptedVault (`backend/vault/encrypted_vault.py`).
Before suggesting a commit: scan diff for strings matching `[A-Za-z0-9]{20,}` in non-test files.

## Trading Safety
All order execution defaults to `dry_run=True`. Production requires explicit `DRY_RUN=false` in env.
Use ccxt sandbox mode in dev: `exchange.set_sandbox_mode(True)`.
Circuit breakers: halt agent if PnL drop > threshold, same error >3x, or order rate exceeded.

## Error Handling
Max 3 retries with exponential backoff (1s, 2s, 4s). After 3 failures: log + mark agent DEGRADED.
Never retry: 401, 403, 400, 404.
Never disable SSL verification (`verify=False`).

## Shell Commands
Prefer quiet flags: `pytest -q`, `pip install -q`, `git diff --stat` before `git diff`.
No `subprocess.shell=True` with user input. No `os.system()` with interpolated vars.

## Permissions
No `sudo` in generated code. No wildcard CORS in production. No `GRANT ALL` on DB.
Minimum required scope only.

## Before Any Implementation
1. Clarify intent if spec is unclear — ask, don't guess.
2. Break task into discrete steps.
3. One file/function at a time.
4. Leave one runnable check for non-trivial logic (assert-based, no frameworks).
